10.20 am Australia are two wickets away from batting again. They haven't faced much problems getting rid of India's tail and knowing that, Kohli's dismissal in the last over of the day was crucial as he was farming the strike well and had added 28 for the eighth wicket, preventing a sudden implosion. The pitch report says that footmarks have started to appear but they are not likely to play a big role in this match.. the drop-in pitch will continue to be good for batting. Some chance of showers in the afternoon.

ose: "I suspect that India's three pace bowlers will be under tremendous pressure this morning. Before their 'normal' duties start, they have to add as many runs as possible. Australia will be not only keen to deny them any, but may also be subjected to bodyline attack to physically/mentally weaken them, before they come on to open the bowling for India. Especially after seeing how things have heated up to such an extent. Waiting anxiously for the day's proceedings to start."

10.10 am Virat Kohli and Ajinkya Rahane's fantastic innings lit up the day yesterday after Steven Smith's glittering innings on day two. It's been a match where the bowlers had to work very hard for wickets. Eighteen batsmen were dismissed in the first three days and it remains to be seen if we are going to get a faster rate of dismissals. At the moment though, India's response with the bat has meant both teams are more or less at the same level with Australia looking likely to take lead. But day four will tell us which way this match is swinging.

The contest continued even after the day's play. Kohli was in combative mood when he came to the presser, saying things like, "I respect some of them", Australia were calling him "spoilt brat" and that it only fired him, so Australia "were not learning a lesson". Ryan Harris' response was that every one in the Australia dressing room respected Kohli's batting. He said further, "It's interesting to hear him say [all] that. It's probably a good thing. Because he's probably worried about that. We need him to worry about that instead of batting."

5.54 pm And that's the end of play today. Kohli walks back to a standing ovation. His magnificent 169, and his mammoth partnership with Ajinkya Rahane ensured India didn't fall back too far behind in the Test. Australia picked up two wickets in the first session but it was the Rahane-Kohli show from there on till after tea. Both the batsmen dominated a disciplined attack, kept the scoring rate up, survived a couple of chances, and then tired them into submission. There was a brief collapse after Rahane's dismissal, as debutant KL Rahul failed to make much of the opportunity and MS Dhoni and R Ashwin fell in quick succession, but Kohli's stand with Shami ensured India did not succumb in a hurry. Australia look set to take the lead with only two wickets in hand for India, but a solid fight back from India today has meant the deciding rounds of this bout are yet to come. Thanks for your comments and feedback. See you tomorrow. Ciao ciao.
